Eric Benhamou was introduced by CEA President and CEO Gary Shapiro. Benhamou has been with 3Com since 1990 and has seen it become a Fortune 300 company as well as a part of the President's Technology Information Advisory Committee. The focus of Benhamou's message was a more connected life in the new millennium:
<p>
We are meeting here at CES only a few days into the New Year and at the dawn of a brand new millenium:
 	We will  be taking lessons from the past to help prepare for the future,   reviewing  lists of facts, people and events.  I feel that beginnings are always auspicious times for hope.
<p>
 	The economy is humming and productivity is high.  In general, we are living in a period of unprecedented prosperity.  The Internet has brought us a new economic order.  It has caused fundamental changes in our lifestyle-a more connected life.   We are more connected to our colleagues at work, our friends and family,  and  to sources of information in general.
<p>
 	Nokia, a company which prides itself on connecting people, has predicted there will be more than one billion cell phones in use around the world shortly. Consumer electronic devices will be made more personal.  3Com creates these connections.   We are  intent on providing the infrastructure that helps facilitate a "more connected lifestyle."
<p>
Our company is only 20 years old and we now have $6 billion in revenues and 13,000 people making up our community.  By now, we have made over 300 million connections all over the world.  It took us 10 years to make the first million connections - and the rest have occurred since.  We will be dealing in billions of connections in the near future.  
<p>
We all have to think on a larger scale for the next frontier:  the home.  The obstacles to overcome will be the requirement of simplicity and the need for reliability.    The nature of connections is changing and becoming more intelligent.   There is a strong desire for access to smart technology.  We live in the world of E.   You need an E-network.  This is who we are and what we do.
<p>
Our theme, "More Connected to :Lifestyle," can be examined by introducing you to a typical family.  They are middle class and they utilize technology in their every day lifestyles. 
<p>
The following describes the family and how they put technology to work for them:
<p>
Mark, the father, works from home and also has the primary job of caring for the family.<br>
Jane, the mother, works in a business that calls for her to travel.  She frequently goes on business trips.<br>
Judy, 16, the daughter, aspires to be an anthropologist.<br>
Anthony, age 12, the son, is a seventh grader.<br>
Max, the dog, is a five-year-old lab who favors chasing the mailman.
<p>
A typical day: The day starts at 6:00am.  At 6:15am, Mark and Jane synchronize their palm pilots to find out about each other's schedules.  At 6:30am, Jane wakes up the children and braces for a busy day in the office, plus leaving later on that day for a trip to Los Angeles.
<p>
Their  home is connected to the Internet using broadband.  This is a key enabler of home networking.  Two million households are connected to broadband networks.  
<p>
Broadband provides a rich set of services, including video.  Different family members utilize broadband for different reasons - shopping, reviewing stock portfolios or downloading the latest music.  Inside the home is a home network that doesn't use any special wiring.  You can do simple things using standard phone lines-simplicity is the key.
<p>
You also can go to a kiosk in an airport and type in your home phone number and the computer will assist you and tell you how your home can most readily be accessed.  
<p>
Just last fall, 3Com introduced a home network which operates using only existing phone lines.
Back to the story, it is now around 7:00am, and Mark begins working.  He starts the day  checking his stock portfolio.  He also plans for the family dinner that evening.  
<p>
Judy can be found online doing color coordination of clothing to be worn that day by her and her friends.  She next downloads music. All of these activities are carried out simultaneously-convergence  is taking place on the same broadband  connection. 
<p>
Now, it is 7:30am, and Anthony doesn't feel well and comes downstairs.  Mark determines that his son is sick and calls the family doctor for an Internet appointment.  He sends Anthony back to bed and goes about his business.  It is now 9:30 and he calls the doctor across a video conferencing line-and the doctor performs a video conferencing exam. Looking through the video camera, the doctor determines  that Anthony has the chickenpox!  Anthony will have to spend the rest of the week in bed.
<p>
This is a simple video conference-a home connect video camera that anyone can use was demonstrated.  A connection was opened and a video conference demonstration ensued. 
<p>


	
		
	



