<p>
Wireless networks are a key ingredient in a more connected lifestyle.
There is another wireless technology known as "Bluetooth."  Bluetooth is named for a ninth century Danish king famous for uniting warring factions.  
<p>
This is a type of network that could be used to unite pagers, Palm Pilots, telephones and more, utilizing the Bluetooth link.   
<p>
These devices recognize each other, synchronize and are simple to use. Special purpose devices will be seen more often, especially within the home environment. 
<p>
How do these special purpose devices integrate themselves into the lifestyle of our family?  Jane, at work and leaving for the airport, checks her palm device and checks that her flight is on time.  Next, she checks her e-mail.  Then, she checks with Mark only to find out that Anthony is ill, and of course, feels guilty.  She makes it to the airport by 4:30pm.
<p>
Next, she walks into her Los Angeles office and beams her Palm Pilot at a co-worker's phone.  The phone is now transformed into  a full Internet appliance.  
<p>
Benhamou introduces a 3Com General Manager who goes into more detail on the Internet appliances.   He uses his cell phone to demonstrate how a phone can be used as an Internet appliance.  
<p>
Benhamou next demonstrated the "click and dial" capabilities--unregistering from the one phone and directing his calls to his home phone, and then changing it to access the Internet.  He explained:
Phones are now in lab trials and will go into field trials this coming spring.  They should be on the market shortly after that. This technology is anticipated to change the industry game and constitutes a deregulation in the technology industry. 3Com is extremely excited about the Internet appliances which will represent a true "breakthrough" in the consumer market and everyday life.
<p>
It will be possible for appliances such as stoves, refrigerators, toasters, etc. to have their maintenance managed remotely by the owner, or by the people providing the maintenance services.  Home technology as part of the family's everyday life is currently being featured by 3Com during  CES.  The aim is to help people achieve more connected lives.
<p>
The next example of incorporating technology into family life was shown in a  video of a family spread throughout the world - while planning their upcoming  family reunion. They were able to coordinate everyone's travel schedules  and take care of  other details, including ordering the food and wine for the event.  The video showed that people can seamlessly incorporate this technology into typical  life events.
<p>
Benhamou said this can all be done with current off-the-shelf technology with the emphasis on simplicity and reliability!  We are  not quite there yet-there are still software crashes and time spent holding on the line, but we  have now survived Y2K, so we   are definitely on the way.
<p>
The impact of this more connected lifestyle is reflected in our daily activities and in society at large.  We actually will think differently as a result of this more connected lifestyle.   In addition, people are subjected to more information than ever before.
<p>
While we may have dealt with a scarcity of  facts in the past, we now are dealing with information that has reached the saturation point, in many cases.   The mind has to synthesize all this and not get lost.   We must combine the content and context with the maturity of our judgment.  
<p>
 	The young minds we want to shape in our schools are facing many changes in educational techniques and priorities.  We might be tempted to believe that just because we are so "well connected," that this is synonymous with having good relationships, but it is not.  The relationships must pre-exist before they can be enhanced with technology.  We live in communities - not necessarily "virtual communities."  While AOL and e-bay talk about communities, I am talking about geographic communities. 
In some communities, schools, fire departments, hospitals, etc. pool their resources for better E-service.  Children can apply for library cards online, while business people can apply for permits online, and others may have easy access to maps in the community.  He said this makes for a more efficient community.   For instance, the mayor and the superintendent of schools may have come together for this purpose, and it benefits society at large.  In this sense, the Internet can offer a sense of renewal.  
<p>
A digital divide exists today between the digital "haves" and"have-nots."  The Department of Commerce recently came out with a report entitled, "Falling through the Net."  There exists a division between white and non-white households.  While both groups recently have become more connected, the gap has not closed.  It does not seem to be a question of race, but rather, income levels.  It is hard to envision a harmonious society with these gaps existing.
<p>
President Clinton has encouraged community access centers for environmentally challenged areas, so that the gaps can close.    3Com also has initiated a coalition for the City of Boston to help with wiring classrooms.  The results have been quite remarkable.  There have been changes in curriculums as well as in training of teachers in connected environments.
<p>
3Com has also participated in the YWCA's "Connected Entrepreneurs'  Program," for business start-ups in economically challenged areas.  We anticipate some valuable mentorship from this source.  We are trying to do our part in closing this "digital divide" and contributing to a better quality of life.
Benhamou finished saying "this is a great industry…and I am happy for this opportunity to come together."



		
